China's State Environmental Protection Administration holds the Jilin Petroleum and Chemical Company accountable for a chemical plant explosion that polluted the Songhua River.
Harbin residents stock up on water as officials shut down the water supply due to contamination.
The toxic benzene and nitrobenzene spill is expected to reach Harbin, prompting emergency measures.
China and Russia collaborate to address the pollution, with China updating Russia on monitoring results.
Efforts to mitigate the pollution include increased water discharge and monitoring.
The government vows to crack down on polluting enterprises and prioritize environmental protection for the next 15 years.
